rts abroad. These outreaches include building orphanages, starting microbusinesses, and setting up computer networks. Drawing on a comprehensive survey that was conducted for this book, as well as several hundred in-depth interviews with church leaders, Wuthnow refutes several prevailing stereotypes: that U.S. churches have turned away from the global church and overseas missions, that congregations only look inward, and that the growing voice of religion in areas of foreign policy is primarily evangelical. This fresh and revealing book encourages Americans to pay attention to the grass-roots mechanisms by which global ties are created and sustained.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aRELIGION / Christianity / General.2bisacsh  aamerican christianity.  aamerican christians.  aamerican policy.  aamerican politics.  aamerican religion.  abuilding orphanages.  achristianity.  achurch leaders.  achurches.  acomputer networks.  acongregations.  adirect engagement.  aevangelical.  aforeign policy.  aglobal church.  aglobalization.  agrass roots mechanisms.  aheterogeneity.  ainequality.  amicro businesses.  amissionaries.  aoverseas mission.  aprayer.  apreachers.  areligion.  areligious advocacy.  areligious.  ashort term volunteer efforts.  asocial organization.  aspiritual.  astereotypes.  avoice of religion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025915740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094306340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520943063423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520943063/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alle